      <div type="commentary"><!--commentary encoded as per section §9.3 --><!-- findspot Banpur in the district of Puri in Orissa
            Date of discovery 1963 while digging for laying the foundation of the local college
            First deceiphered by Dr K. B. Trripathy in the Oriya Journal the Jhankāra n° X p.661-668
            First edited by Dr K. B. Trripathy in the Journal of the Asicatic Society vol VIII n°4 109966 p 271-276
            According to Behera1988_01 the charter is now kept in the department of History, Utkal University
            According to Behera1988_01 the characters are similar to those found in the copper plate grants of Dharmaratha and Uddyotakesari
            Influence of local prononciation on orthographical peculiarities
            Charter issued from Yayātinagara
            Registers grant of the village Laghukumbhi situated in the khaṇḍa of Sadyatukhallī in the viṣaya of Thoraṇa in Kongada-maṇḍala
            Donor . Indraratha
            Recipient Khadiravaṇī Bhaṭṭārikā
            Written by Amṛtacandra
            Interesting detail . first verse invocation to śiva
            Genealogy . important because as Behera1988_01 remarks page 39 "the ruler indraratha is new in this record and he is not met with in the Brahmeśvara isncription of Uddyotakesari's reign (Soma30) and the Ratnagiri grant of Karṇadeva which provide the complete genealogical table of the Somavaṃśi dynasty. In the Banpur charter Indraratha is mentioned as born in the lunar family. He was the son of Bhīma who is identical with Bhīmaratha (Mahābhavagupta II son and successor of Yayāti Mahāśivagupta I). He had two younger brothers, viz., Vaṅkaratha and Śankararatha who are noticed in any other record. Indraratha is said to have won the royal fortune of Kaliṅga being a favourite of Dharmaratha (Khandapara grant)"
            See Mallaram charter Śaktivarman I who claims the victory over Dharmarath and Indra note 6 the Mallavaram Plates of Paraantaaka in Copper plate Inscriptions of Andhra Pradesh Government Museum p.89-90
            Vatsarāja is probably a feudatory of the Paramāra king Sindhurāja note 7 OHRJ vol XXXIII n 1 & 2 p.164
            From the Udayapur Praśāsti Indraratha seems to have been defeated by the Paramāra king Bhoja (1001-1047) note 9 : History and Culture of the Indian people vol V p 66
            Tirumalai Inscription of Rajendra Coḷa (1012-1044) 13 Ry (1024) . this king captured Indraratha
